text: Received 14th July 2018, Accepted 25th September 2018 Three kinds of hydrophobic/acidic bifunctional ionic liquids, which contain two diﬀerent anions, were synthesized and utilized as catalysts for the conversion of cellulosic saccharides into alkyl glucosides, which exhibit a high catalytic conversion for cellobiose and cellulose with a low degree of crystallinity; the catalyst can be easily recovered and reused. Diminishing fossil fuel reserves and growing global environ- mental awareness of the impact of their use have triggered intense research into renewable rather than depleting sources.1 Wind, water, solar power, and biomass are regarded as such resources.2 Cellulose and lignocellulose are promising alternatives of renewable feedstocks for sustainable production of platform chemicals and fuels.3 As a result, diﬀerent routes for cellulose conversion, including pyrolysis, gasification, and enzymatic fermentation have been developed; however these approaches involve high reaction temperatures and long reaction times, resulting in high energy consumption and low product yield.4 Thus a selective catalytic route under mild conditions for the conversion of cellulose into platform molecules is highly desirable.5 However, the reaction chemistry of cellulose is impeded by its strong bound crystalline structure. Recently, ionic liquids (ILs), as a new class of cellulose processing solvent system, have attracted more attention.6 Since Rogers’ group reported that cellulose was soluble in 1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium chloride ([BMIm][Cl]) IL,7 a number of studies have investigated its use

A diverse family of ILs have been reported to dissolve cellulose,8 and also to be useful as a reaction medium in which to carry out cellulose transforma- tions, using a variety of acidic and other types of catalysts.5,9

Alkyl glucosides are promising value-added chemicals, usually prepared by alcoholysis of cellulose. They are typically excellent surfactants with low toxicity and good biodegradability, and are widely used in the cosmetics, food, and pharmaceutical industries.10 Alcoholysis of cellulose without catalysts can only proceed under relatively extreme conditions; for example the highest yield of methyl-a,b-glucosides of B30% is obtained at 623 K and 43 MPa.11 Catalytic alcoholysis can be carried out in methanol by using heteropolyacids such as H3PW12O40 and H4SiW12O40 as catalysts under relatively mild conditions. A yield of 440% of methyl glucosides is obtained at 468 K and 3 MPa.12 Although a higher yield of ethyl glucosides of 63% was produced in the further study, the low solubility of cellulose in alcohols and its intrinsic crystalline structure are unfavourable for the conversion and high energy costs are still incurred due to the high temperature and pressure.13 Alternatively, Villandier and Corma showed that by working in [BMIm][Cl] IL media and coupling cellulose hydrolysis and glycosidation of the resultant monosaccharides into one process, it is possible to convert cellulose into octylglucosides with 82% mass yield using an acidic resin (Amberlyst-15Dry) as a catalyst.14 Almost at the same time, de Vos and Ignatyev et al. reported the same phenomenon, with an 86% yield of butylglucopyranoside (BGS) isomers in [BMIm][Cl] IL.15 Thus, much higher yields of alkyl glucosides can be achieved in solid acid catalyst/IL systems; however, the recovery of the product from the IL and its purity remain as challenges in turning this strategy into a practical reality. There- fore, the development of novel, functional ILs combining ease of separation from the products and a high catalytic activity for alcoholysis of cellulose is highly desirable. Very recently, Yuan and Chen et al. investigated the alcoholysis of cellulosic saccharides using PVP stabilized heteropolyacids as catalysts

Very recently, Yuan and Chen et al. investigated the alcoholysis of cellulosic saccharides using PVP stabilized heteropolyacids as catalysts, the IL-like catalyst PVP-H4SiW12O40(cid:2)5H2O (1/5 : 3/4) could be reused for several cycles with more than 60% conversion of cellulose.16

Scheme 1 Synthesized BFILs. However, to date, few studies have described alcoholysis of cellulosic saccharides using ILs as the catalyst.17 Herein, we report a class of hydrophobic and acidic bifunc- tional ILs (BFILs) containing two diﬀerent anions (Scheme 1), in which the part of propanesulfonic acid combined with [CH3SO3](cid:3) endows the quality of a Bro¨nsted acidic catalyst, while the other part combined with [NTf2](cid:3) facilitates the separation of BFILs from water after the reaction by enhancing the hydrophobicity of BFILs, and utilize them as catalysts for the conversion of cellulosic saccharides into alkyl glucosides in alcohol solvents under mild conditions. These BFILs can catalyze the alcoholysis of cellobiose and cellulose with a low degree of crystallinity, producing high yields of long chain alkyl glucosides.

The BFILs were prepared using an established method18 except that the two diﬀerent anions were introduced in two steps by controlling the molar ratio of the corresponding reactants. In order to facilitate the introduction of the two diﬀerent anions by reaction, bis(1-imidazolyl)methane, 4,40-dipyridyl, and N,N,N0,N0-tetramethylethane-1,2-diamine were respectively chosen as starting materials. The yields of these BFILs attained were in the range of 74.4–96.1%. Mass spectra (MS) (Fig. S16–S18, ESI†), respectively, confirm that the resulting compounds have the desired structures although there is a tiny peak (m/z = 262) of ions, which may be related to N,N0-dibutyl-bis- fragment (1-imidazolyl)methane that existed in the cationic MS of BFIL1. For example, different nominal structures for fragment ions such as m/z = 125, 187 and 205.1, which are in agreement with the fragmentation of 1-butylimidazole, N-propanesulfonylimizazolium and N-butyl, N0-H-bis(1-imidazolyl)methane derived from BFIL1, respectively, were found in MS (Fig. S16, ESI†) except that the base peak (m/z = 327.6) for the cation indicates the desired cationic structure. Furthermore, the compared NMR data also confirm the desired structures of the BFILs. In the case of BFIL1, the 13C NMR peaks of 3-methene in the N-propanesulfonic acid group shift to a low field (d = 38.1 ppm) compared to 3-methene (d = 19 ppm) in N-butyl due to the electron-withdrawing inductive effect of S- in sulfonic acid. In comparison with the bis- (1-imidazolyl)methane starting material, after the [NTf2](cid:3) group was introduced by the anion exchange reaction, four characteristic bands appeared at 1351, 1136 cm(cid:3)1 and 1196, 1058 cm(cid:3)1, which are assigned to the stretching modes of SQO and C–F3,19

Fig. 1 (a) IR spectra of Im(CH2)Im, [BIm(CH2)Im][NTf2], and BFIL1; (b) enlarged parts of the Im(CH2)Im and [BIm(CH2)Im][NTf2] spectra; (c) enlarged parts of the [BIm(CH2)Im][NTf2] and BFIL1 spectra. respectively, indicating that [Br](cid:3) was replaced by [NTf2](cid:3) in the second step of the synthesis of BFIL1. Similarly, after the sulfona- tion reaction, bands at 1140, 1230, and 2814 cm(cid:3)1 appeared, which can be assigned to the stretching modes of SQO and S– O–H.20 The thermal stability was characterised by the thermal decomposition temperature (Td), ranging from 569 K to 773 K, indicating that these BFILs are able to be applied in alcoholysis of saccharides without decomposition induced by cellulosic simple heat. These BFILs are insoluble in water and soluble or partly soluble in n-butanol. The comparative acidity of these BFILs, i.e., the Hammett acidity function (H0), was determined spectro- photometrically21 by using 2-phenylazodiphenylamine as an indicator (Fig. S20, ESI†). The H0 order of these BFILs was as follows: H0(BFIL1) o H0(BFIL2) o H0(BFIL3). Thus, BFIL1 has the strongest acidity among them.

Cellobiose, which has the same b-1,4-glycosidic bonds as cellulose, can be considered as the simplest model of cellulose. Thus, studies on the transformation of cellobiose can provide useful insights into the ultimate alcoholysis of cellulose. There- fore, we compared the catalytic performance of the diﬀerent ILs for cellobiose conversion in n-butanol under the optimized reaction conditions (Figs. S23–S25, ESI†). As shown in Table 1, in the absence of a catalyst, there is no conversion of cellobiose at 368 K. The butanolysis was then carried out in the presence of a conventional IL, [BMIm][PF6]; the yield was negligible, although the separation of the product/catalyst is easy due to its hydro- phobicity (entries 1 and 2). However, when literature Bro¨nsted acidic ILs (BAILs)22 were introduced as catalysts, low to high conversions of cellobiose accompanied by a good BGS selectivity were obtained under the same conditions, due to the enhanced apparent acidity of the catalyst. For example, using a caprolactam trifluoroacetate ([CP][TFA]) catalyst, the weakest acid among the BAILs studied, the conversion of cellobiose was only 9.1% with a 99.5% selectivity towards BGS (entry 3). The conversion of cellobiose increased with the apparent acidity of the BAILs, and a 53.6% conversion accompanied by a 99.7% selectivity was Table 1 Butanolysis of cellobiose catalyzed by diﬀerent ILsa 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9c 10d 11 12 a Reaction conditions: 0.10 g cellobiose, 0.02 g catalyst, and 5 mL n-butanol at 368 K for 4 h. b The conversion and selectivity were determined by HLPC. c The recovered BFIL1 was reused. d The same amount of fresh BFIL1 as in entry 9 was used. e G = glucose, L = butyl levulinate.

obtained in the presence of the [CP][BF4] BAIL (entry 6). It is obvious that the yield of BGS is far lower than that (86%) obtained by de Vos and Ignatyev et al. using Amberlyst-15Dry as a catalyst in [BMIm][Cl] IL. Furthermore, in order to separate BGS from the reacted mixtures, other chemicals such as dibutylether need to be added as extractants, resulting in a burdensome process.

The structural ideas explored in this work were stimulated by the observation that a 99.4% conversion of cellobiose accompanied by a 98.5% BGS selectivity can be obtained by using the sulfonic acid functionalised BAIL 1-(3-sulfonic acid)- propyl-3-methyl imidazolium mesylate ([MIm(CH2)3SO3H]) [CH3SO3]23 as a catalyst (entry 7). This may be attributed to the interaction of the H(cid:2) (cid:2) (cid:2)O–SO2-group and the b-1,4-glucan groups of cellobiose.9a However, this also suffers from difficult product/catalyst separation issues. Hence our dicationic struc- tures allowed the inclusion of a –SO3H group as well as a [NTf2](cid:3) anion to strengthen its hydrophobicity, facilitating the product separation process. When BFIL1 was applied to catalyze butanolysis of cellobiose, the conversion and BGS selectivity were 99.1% and 99.0%, respectively, (entry 8). After the reaction, the product was separated from the resultant mixtures by simply adding distilled water. The BFIL1 was recovered and recycled by removing part of the n-butanol and traces of water under vacuum and then reusing it directly. The recovered BFIL1 showed nearly equivalent catalytic activity as the same amount of fresh catalyst (entries 9 and 10). Further- more, in comparation with the pristine one, mass spectrometry showed that there was no destruction of the recovered BFIL1 (Figs. S16 and S19, ESI†). Therefore, the comparative decrease of cellobiose conversion (99.1% vs. 94.9%) is mainly caused by the slight loss of catalyst (0.8%) in the process of recovery. Next, the recyclability of BFIL1 was investigated in the following consecutive experiments. As shown in Fig. 2, it is obvious that the recovered BFIL1 keeps high catalytic performance in at least five recycling runs. Thus, it appears that the catalytic performance of BFILs for alcoholysis of cellobiose in n-butanol is related to their intrinsic acidity.

Having confirmed the high catalytic performance of these BFILs in the alcoholysis of cellobiose, we next investigated the eﬀect on cellulose conversion. As shown in Table 2, it is diﬃcult to convert cellulose of 85% crystallinity directly into BGS at 413 K (entry 1). In order to decrease the crystallinity, cellulose was ball-milled for diﬀerent times. The XRD patterns showed that the degree of crystallinity of cellulose decreased with an increase in the milling time (Fig. S21, ESI†). Accordingly, the conversion increased; for example, a 32.1% conversion was obtained when cellulose was milled for 48 h (entry 3). A much higher conversion (68.3%) was obtained when a lower crystal- linity cellulose was used (entry 5). After 120 h of milling, a conversion of 90.4% accompanied by a 99.6% selectivity was obtained (entry 6). Further investigations of the alcoholysis of cellulose of low crystallinity catalyzed by BFIL1 were carried out in diﬀerent alcohols. In comparison with the result in n-butanol, the lower yield of hexyl glucosides may be due to the lower solubility of cellulose in the longer chain, and the more hydrophobic alcohols.14 On the other hand, the stronger hydro- gen bond donor of the smaller alcohols favors the glycosidic bond cleavage of cellulose to form glucosides with alkoxyl groups, resulting in the higher yield of methyl glucoside (93.6%). The results of cellulose alcoholysis in n-octanol and ethanol respectively again verified a better catalytic perfor- mance of BFIL1 in short chain alcohol (entries 9 and 10).

Long chain alkyl glucosides such as dodecyl polyglucoside are more prevalent in practical applications because of their strong detergency, biodegradability, and non-toxicity. There- fore, we further explored the transalkylation of methyl and butylglucosides, catalyzed by BFIL1, in long chain alcohols. The results in Table 3 demonstrate that this transalkylation of methyl glucoside occurs readily in n-octanol and n-dodecanol, and that the yields of octyl and dodecyl glucosides were 82.7% and 74.1%, respectively. Slightly lower yields were attained using BGS. Thus it appears that alcoholysis followed by trans- alkylation is a feasible approach to the conversion of cellulose into long chain alkyl glucosides. In summary, several hydrophobic and acidic BFILs contain- ing two diﬀerent anions have been successfully synthesized and applied as catalysts for cellulosic saccharide conversion. These BFILs exhibit useful catalytic behavior for the conversion of cellobiose and cellulose into alkyl glucosides directly or indirectly under mild conditions. Furthermore, these water insoluble BFILs can facilitate the product separation, and can be recovered and recycled conveniently.
